{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3369502,"name":"Dan Langdon","username":"woodworker2001","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/w/bbe5ce/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-04-22T16:20:45.075Z","cooked":"<p>Our shooterRotation subsytem basically had 4 modes or states: Speaker Tracking, Intake, Amp Score, and Climbing.</p>
<p>I am attempting to figure out ways to take our programming up a level in the future.  This year we just used boolean variables to keep tract of what state it was in and wrote methods that set all of them to false except the mode we wanted to enter.</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">public void setAmpMode() { // sets the shooter to our mode that tracks the amp and turns off all other modes
    ampMode = true;
    speakerAngleTracking = false;
    intakeMode = false;
    climbMode = false;
  }
</code></pre>
<p>Obviously each of these states was a different angle we wanted to set the shooter rotation to with speaker tracking being an angle that was calculated by our vision subsystem.  So we just wrote some if logic based on the state of the booleans in the period function of the subsystem to set these angles.</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto"> if (climbMode) {
      setShooterAngle(20);
    }

    else if (speakerAngleTracking) {

      setShooterAngle(photon.getTargetAngle()); // sets shooter to track the
      // speaker
      // setShooterAngle(SmartDashboard.getNumber("TestShooterAngle", 0));
    }
</code></pre>
<p>As I look at many teams codes I see that many seem to be using Enum’s to create these states and so some things with them.  I have done some basic googling on them, but not really following how to implement them or if this is the best way to go about controlling the state of a subsystem.</p>
<p>I feel like this could be applied to LED subsystems pretty easily too and maybe help streamline some of the programing of these to avoid</p>
<p>So are Enums the best way to achieve this?  If so can someone help me with some explanations and code examples?  If not what is the best way to achieve this?</p>","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"posts_count":44,"updated_at":"2024-04-22T16:21:56.409Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":526,"reads":467,"readers_count":466,"score":2733.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":463974,"topic_slug":"enums-and-subsytem-states","display_username":"Dan Langdon","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://www.chiefdelphi.com/t/2024-the-year-in-review/477837/5","internal":true,"reflection":true,"title":"2024: The Year in Review","clicks":0}],"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":1}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":51496,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/enums-and-subsytem-states/463974/1","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":1,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null,"can_vote":false},{"id":3369589,"name":"","username":"ad10bv","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/ad10bv/{size}/182467_2.png","created_at":"2024-04-22T17:08:13.184Z","cooked":"<p>For a set of mutually exclusive states, like those four modes you described, enums are the way to go.</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">//assign an initial state if desired, or decide initial state in subsystem ctor
ShooterMode shooterState = ShooterMode.kSpeakerAngleTracking;

public enum ShooterMode {
    kAmp,
    kSpeakerAngleTracking,
    kIntake,
    kClimb
}
</code></pre>
<p>Inside the class, just reassign the value of the variable to change state. Getters and setters can facilitate access by other classes.<br>
To act on state in a periodic method when using an enum, a switch statement is usually cleaner than an if-else-if statement:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">switch (shooterState) {
     case kClimb:
         setShooterAngle(20);
     break;
     case kSpeakerAngleTracking:
        setShooterAngle(photon.getTargetAngle());
     break;
     //etc
     default:
     break;
}
</code></pre>","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"posts_count":44,"updated_at":"2024-04-22T17:08:13.184Z","reply_count":2,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":8,"reads":352,"readers_count":351,"score":135.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":463974,"topic_slug":"enums-and-subsytem-states","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":1}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":56577,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"3490 programmer"},"post_url":"/t/enums-and-subsytem-states/463974/2","custom_user_title":"3490 programmer","reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":1,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3369594,"name":"Dan Langdon","username":"woodworker2001","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/w/bbe5ce/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-04-22T17:12:31.568Z","cooked":"<p>So I was playing with writing Code… I think I can to basically what you have…</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">  private enum ShooterRotationState{
    SpeakerTracking,
    AmpMode,
    ClimbMode,
    Intake;
  };

  private ShooterRotationState shooterRotationState;
  private double targetAngle;
</code></pre>
<p>In periodic:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">switch (shooterRotationState) {
      case SpeakerTracking:
        targetAngle = photon.getTargetAngle();
        break;

      case AmpMode:
        if (photon.getAmpDistance() &lt; 2) targetAngle = ShooterConstants.kAmpAngle; // sets shooter to point for shooting into amp if within 1 meter of it
        else targetAngle = 100 ; // sets shooter to flat if not within 1 meter

        break;

      case ClimbMode:
        targetAngle = ShooterConstants.kClimbAngle;
        break;

      case Intake:
        targetAngle = ShooterConstants.kIntakeAngle;

      default:
        break;
    }

    setShooterAngle(targetAngle);

</code></pre>
<p>Then a method for changing the current state:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">public void setShooterRotationState(ShooterRotationState state){
    shooterRotationState = state;
  }```</code></pre>","post_number":3,"post_type":1,"posts_count":44,"updated_at":"2024-04-22T17:12:31.568Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":2,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":12,"reads":318,"readers_count":317,"score":123.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":463974,"topic_slug":"enums-and-subsytem-states","display_username":"Dan Langdon","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":56577,"username":"ad10bv","name":"","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/ad10bv/{size}/182467_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":51496,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/enums-and-subsytem-states/463974/3","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3369596,"name":"Brad","username":"Bmongar","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/bmongar/{size}/228654_2.png","created_at":"2024-04-22T17:12:45.303Z","cooked":"<p>Even clean would be to make the enum also an <a href="https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/how-to-implement-a-strategy-pattern-using-enum-in-java/#" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">implementation of a strategy</a> .</p>
